T1  - Selecting Foreign Plant Sites: Economic, Social and Political Considerations
AU  - Bass, Bernard M.
AU  - McGregor, Donald W.
AU  - Walters, James L.
Y1  - 1977/12/01
PY  - 1977
DA  - 1977/12/01
N1  - doi: 10.5465/255355
DO  - 10.5465/255355
T2  - Academy of Management Journal
JF  - Academy of Management Journal
JO  - AMJ
SP  - 535
EP  - 551
VL  - 20
IS  - 4
PB  - Academy of Management
N2  - Completed survey responses about 118 recently built plant sites in Latin America, Europe, or Asia, were obtained from an original list of 175 U. S. firms. Direct investment followed increasing sales growth, local demand, host government's cooperativeness, stability and honesty, as well as favorable labor relations and infrastructure. While the data suggest that a team of executives will reach a more satisfactory siting decision than one working alone, there was no one best set of criteria for the decision in different countries and industries.
AB  - Completed survey responses about 118 recently built plant sites in Latin America, Europe, or Asia, were obtained from an original list of 175 U. S. firms. Direct investment followed increasing sales growth, local demand, host government's cooperativeness, stability and honesty, as well as favorable labor relations and infrastructure. While the data suggest that a team of executives will reach a more satisfactory siting decision than one working alone, there was no one best set of criteria for the decision in different countries and industries.
